data.content:
In xUnit:

- **`[SetUp]`** → **constructor** (xUnit creates a new instance per test)
- **`[TearDown]`** → **`IDisposable.Dispose()`**
- **`[OneTimeSetUp/TearDown]`** → **`IClassFixture<T>`** with a shared fixture class

Here's the converted code:

```csharp
// Shared fixture for one-time setup/teardown
public class DatabaseFixture : IDisposable
{
    public DatabaseFixture()
    {
        Database.Initialize();
    }

    public void Dispose()
    {
        Database.Cleanup();
    }
}

public class CustomerRepositoryTests : IClassFixture<DatabaseFixture>, IDisposable
{
    private readonly DbContext _context;
    private readonly CustomerRepository _repo;

    // Replaces [SetUp] — runs before each test
    public CustomerRepositoryTests(DatabaseFixture fixture)
    {
        _context = new TestDbContext();
        _repo = new CustomerRepository(_context);
    }

    // Replaces [TearDown] — runs after each test
    public void Dispose()
    {
        _context.Dispose();
    }

    [Fact]
    public void FindById_ExistingCustomer_ReturnsCustomer()
    {
        var customer = _repo.FindById(1);
        Assert.NotNull(customer);
        Assert.Equal("Alice", customer.Name);
    }
}
```

Key differences:
- **`IClassFixture<T>`** — the fixture is created once and injected via the constructor; disposed after all tests complete
- **Constructor** — xUnit instantiates the class per test, so the constructor *is* your per-test setup
- **`IDisposable`** — on the test class itself handles per-test teardown
- **`[Fact]`** replaces `[Test]`; assertions use `Assert.Equal(expected, actual)` order
